<HEAD>Paterson Man Turns Himself In After Being Sought For Shooting Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who fled the shooting of his wife crashed his car, took over two other vehicles at gunpoint and left an abducted family beside a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> highway before surrendering Friday, police said. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Otero </PERSON>, 39, was wanted for the Thursday night shooting of his estranged wife, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Otero </PERSON>, 34. She was in critical condition Friday night at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said a nursing superviser. <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> turned himself in to <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION> police about 5 p.m. Friday and was arrested on charges of attempted murder, kidnapping, armed robbery and unlawful possession of a weapon, said police Sgt. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Perrone </PERSON>. <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> was held in the city jail pending arraignment Saturday. Police said the shooting began an interstate trek across the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and a manhunt that involved police from <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> shot his wife several times about 10:15 p.m. Thursday and fled in his own car only to get into an accident with other cars a few blocks away. Witnesses told police <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> pulled a revolver and forced <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Vazquez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION> to drive him to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vazquez </PERSON> dropped <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> off near the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> end of the <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tunnel </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, police said. There, <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> approached a car stopped at a pay phone and forced five members of a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> family to drive him to <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, said Officer <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Swinney </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police spokeswoman. A male family member was at a pay phone when <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> allegedly forced him back into the car and made them drive to <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` I thought he was going to kill us for sure,'' said <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Gee </PERSON>, whose husband, daughter, son, and grandson were held at gunpoint during the two-hour ordeal. `` We started to pray out loud as soon as he got into the car,'' Mrs. Gee said. `` He told us to shut up.'' The gunman forced the family, which was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to attend a funeral service, out of the car on the Long Island Expressway near <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Westbury </LOCATION>, police said. <PERSON> Perrone </PERSON> said there were no reports of injuries to the family or <PERSON> Vazquez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Otero </PERSON> then fled on foot. He contacted his relatives while on the run and was talked into giving himself up, <PERSON> Perrone </PERSON> said.
