<HEAD>Senators Call for End to Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-one senators have lined up against their steel-state colleagues and called on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to end steel import quotas covering 19 nations and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The senators said in a letter Friday to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that the restraints have driven up steel prices and caused product shortages. They said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needed `` a sensible steel policy'' that considered not just steelmakers, but other producers, too. The senators, 18 of them <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION>, face stiff opposition. Fifty-five other senators, many of them from steel-producing states, have signed onto a bill empowering the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to extend the import curbs beyond their Sept. 30 expiration. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration negotiated five-year, product-by-product `` voluntary restraint agreements'' in 1984 with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and other nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Three days before last November's election, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pledged to continue the restraints in some form. But with the steel industry newly profitable, opponents of the curbs _ led by a coalition of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers _ believe they can make a case for ending the program, or at least narrowing its scope. Manufacturers of home appliances, construction and farm machinery, industrial equipment, auto parts and other products all rely on steel as a raw material, said the letter to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` In the experience of many of these manufacturers, steel voluntary restraint agreements have caused higher prices and shortages of some steel products, and are undermining their ability to compete in international markets,'' the letter said. `` It is important that steel trade be considered from the perspective of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers, not just the steel industry alone,'' it said. The senators invited <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to end the `` burden'' of the quotas. But Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., a leading advocate of continued restraints, said through a spokesman Friday that the conditions that compelled steel firms to seek government aid in 1984 remain `` There are still some senators who keep their heads in the sand when it comes to the fact that countries have not discontinued their unfair trading practices of dumping and subsidies,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryers </PERSON>, legislative director for <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>. Signing the letter to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were Sens. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash.; <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Boschwitz </PERSON>, R-Minn.; <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>,; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Thad </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, R-Miss.; <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif.; <PERSON> Slade </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorton </PERSON>, R-Wash.; <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore.; <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON>, R-Kan.; <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>, R-Wis.; <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, D-Wis.; <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore.; <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>,; <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>.; and <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif
