<HEAD>Senators Keep PAC Money They Claim is Tainted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senators say they'll keep $ 8,000 in campaign contributions from an imported-car dealers' group, even though both complained the organization is a foreign agent forbidden to make such payments. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drivers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PAC </ORGANIZATION> gave $ 5,000 to Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and $ 3,000 to Sen. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> last year, it also spent nearly $ 1 million to defeat them and Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Nev </LOCATION>. Those three senators, along with Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., signed a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asking it to investigate whether the PAC ought to be registered as a foreign If the organization were found to be a foreign agent operating with foreign funds, spending that money to influence an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> election would be illegal. Nevertheless, neither <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> plan to give the money back unless the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> tells them to do so, their spokesmen said. `` I mean these guys are hypocrites,'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemet </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> PAC </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday. `` They asked us for money to support them.'' <PERSON> Nemet </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Glacken </PERSON>, the imported-auto dealer <ORGANIZATION> PAC </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director, deny they're working for foreigners. The PAC spent