y notes from <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. `` If we'd won the Super Bowl, we'd have been in the Rose Garden. But if you get people blown out of the air, that's not important enough,'' said <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, whose brother was killed in the bombing. A group of Flight 103 victims' relatives proposes that the government set up a telephone number passengers can call to see if there are threats against a flight they are planning to take. Officials in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> disclosed that a bomb warning, including a photograph of a radio-cassette bomb of the type investigators believe was used, was dated two days before the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> 747 was destroyed but did not reach the airlines until several days later. Both British authorities and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> had described such a bomb in security warnings a month earlier, airline and government officials said. The West German intelligence agency said it sent a memo about the possibility of such a bomb to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines even earlier, on Nov. 10. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said he was trying to get more details on the warning and how they were handled. `` Let me tell you I do n't know everything,'' he said. `` Yesterday I learned some things for the first time, and I think the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> did, about some disclosures in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> as well as some possible disclosures to <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> airlines.'' Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> transportation subcommittee, introduced a resolution ur