<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-RebelTown     03-18 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Rebel Town,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Returned Refugees Shun Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Editor's Note _ An <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondent was permitted to spend several days this week in rebel-controlled territory in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Here is his report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MARTA, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 None of the voting-age residents in this village of 2,500 plans to cast a ballot in Sunday's presidential election `` No one here believes in this election,'' said <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lainez </PERSON>, a local leader of this town, which was repopulated in 1987 after being abandoned for seven years. `` This election is to prolong the war,'' said a man who identified himself only as <PERSON> Victor </PERSON>. His comment echoed a refrain broadcast daily on two clandestine guerrilla radio stations of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. No love is lost between <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marta </LOCATION> and the U.S.-backed government of President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>. His administration and its army consider the town, like others revived by people who returned from refugee camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, as hostile territory. <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Marta </PERSON>'s sympathies clearly lie with the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>, the rebel army waging a nine-year war against the government. The rebels have called for an election boycott to prove that a political solution is impossible without their participation. Every day from 6 a.m. to 8 a.m., battery-powered radios in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marta </LOCATION> are tuned to <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venceremos </ORGANIZATION>. Like many rural communities in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, this one lacks electricity. Women grind corn or pat tortillas as men drink coffee before heading to the fields. On one morning this week, all listened to a radio account of overnight attacks on `` the puppet army'' and admonishments that every Salvadoran do his part to prepare for insurrection. Guerrillas wander through this town in <LOCATION> north </LOCATION> <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. They are greeted with smiles and offered cool melon juice. Government soldiers, on their rare appearances, are shunned. `` The soldiers three times set fire to the cornfield around here,'' said <PERSON> Lainez </PERSON>. `` The last time they came through, a few went up to people and told them, ` Just wait until <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> is in power. We'll be back with a bomb for every house.''' <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> of the rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, or <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, is expected to win Sunday's election. In its campaign, <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> has taken a hard line on the war, threatening a military solution. Col. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrarte </PERSON>, the provincial military commander, said in an interview that he hopes to improve relations with <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Marta </PERSON> through more personal contact. But he acknowledges the difficulties. `` The subversives count on them for supplies, recruitment and rest,'' he said. `` They portray us only as murderers, violators of human rights, ogres.'' An estimated 20,000 Salvadorans _ mostly from <LOCATION> Chalatenango </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cabanas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Morazan </LOCATION> provinces _ were driven from their homes by the war, aerial bombardments and repression in the early 1980s. Since October 1987, about 6,500 have returned to rebuild their lives. `` When we came back, this was just woods and brush,'' said <PERSON> Lainez </PERSON>. `` Every house had been burned, and the fields were overgrown.'' He said most residents never lost hope of going home. `` Our umbilical cords are buried here,'' he said, using a Salvadoran expression conveying the importance of one's roots. For their part, the guerrillas refer to the local residents as `` the heroic resettlers of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marta </LOCATION>.'' `` They came back to confront the army without weapons,'' said a local guerrilla commander who identified himself only as <PERSON> Antolin </PERSON>. During its first year of reconstruction, the town depended on charity from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and church groups. But last year yielded a good harvest, and the village is nearly self-sufficient in corn and beans, the daily staples. A walk through the settlement showed residents building latrines, making adobe blocks, working on a chicken coop and pounding dried stalks of millet to separate the kernels from the chaff. Many are enlarging their homes of adobe, mud-and-wattle and corrugated metal roofs. The social arrangement is largely cooperative, with familes permitted small private plots to augment their communal ration. `` Because of the war, there are lots of widows and orphans here,'' said <PERSON> Lainez </PERSON>. `` If we were n't a cooperative, those people would die.'' He said soldiers in the provincial capital of Sensuntepeque often stop trucks headed for <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marta </LOCATION> loaded with donated food, clothing or construction materials. `` They think everything we bring up here is for the guerrillas. But we barely have enough for ourselves and are n't in a position to give things away,'' <PERSON> Lainez </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
