<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passengers aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jetliner sat in stunned silence when a fire on the plane's tail created severe vibrations so severe the pilot made an emergency landing. No one was injured. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 en route from <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> with 69 people aboard landed safely Friday at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, officials said. The vibrations, which began over the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> about 200 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, lasted several minutes and were followed by several minutes of silence on the airliner. `` There was no panic as far as people screaming. It's just that people were quite concerned,'' said R.E. `` Griff'' Greffenius, a business traveler from <LOCATION> Walnut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Officials discovered a charred area about 10 feet in diameter at the rear of the tail There also appeared to be damage to the stabilizer, the horizontal portion of the tail that helps control the plane's altitude. An investigator from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> office examined the plane Friday night, and two more investigators were to arrive today, said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Schleede </PERSON>, chief of the Aviation Accident Division of the safety board Continental officials in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> said they believed the plane's auxiliary power unit, or APU, overheated An aviation source who had a chance to inspect the plane said a fire had damaged the stabilizer on the tail section near the APU, but he said the power unit itself was not charred. `` It -LRB- the stabilizer -RRB- is burned on the outside. The paint is burned off. But they do n't know how it occurred,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said a possibile cause could have had something to do with one of the plane's strobe lights. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Messing </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said there was no indication of sabotage on the twin-engine jet, which carried 64 passengers and a crew of five.
