<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Peace,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government, Guerrillas To Begin Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government and the country's most feared guerrilla group have signed an accord to begin talks toward ending nearly two decades of bloody insurgency. President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> in a nationwide television address Friday night asked the other Colombian rebel groups to follow suit. `` I urge all guerrillas to integrate themselves in civilian life. The road is always open,'' <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> said. An estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas operate in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. They are blamed for more than 2,000 deaths and nearly 500 kidnappings in 1988 alone. The accord was signed Friday in the mountain town of <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Domingo </LOCATION>, 180 miles south of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, by the minister of <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Orejuela </PERSON> <PERSON> Bueno </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Pizarro </PERSON>, commander of the M-19, or the April 19 Movement. The April 19 Movement takes its name from a 1970 presidential election that the guerrillas say was fraudulent. Once the nation's most notorious group, M-19's bloodiest operation was seizing the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> in 1985. The army retook the building, but 11 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices and 85 other people were killed. A joint declaration said four meetings that led to the accord were held in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> after the leftist guerrillas declared a unilateral cease-fire eight months ago. The declaration said both sides agreed on talks beginning April 1 that would `` lead to full democracy'' and reintegrate the insurgents into society. The talks are to finish before legislative elections set for March 1990, in which M-19 probably will participate as a legal political party, officials said. The agreement did not say when the guerrillas would have to give up their arms. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> said the accord `` opens a time of hope for the fate of the country,'' but he said there large obstacles to overcome before attaining peace. He signaled that the government is ready to begin talks with the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colombia </ORGANIZATION>, a communist rebel group that declared a unilateral cease-fire Feb. 28 in an effort to join the peace process. However, <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> said the cease-fire must hold for a certain period of time to determine if the <ORGANIZATION> FARC </ORGANIZATION> has `` a genuine spirit of reconciliation.'' The joint declaration also said the guerrillas will no longer operate underground and will base themselves in <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Domingo </LOCATION>, where they receive state protection and will not be subject to harassment by the army. During the signing ceremony, <PERSON> Orejuela </PERSON> said all sides must stay vigilant because `` there are people interested in seeing that a process like this one fails.'' The declaration said 13 guerrilla delegates who had no criminal record participated in the talks and had government protection.
