<FIRST>r i PM-GreatWall     03-18 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Great Wall,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans Canceled For Cable Car Up China's Great Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mayor of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> has halted plans to build a cable car up the side of the Great Wall, yielding to preservationists who said it would desecrate <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous landmark, official newspapers said today. The battle over the cable car had been fought for two years, with the main support coming from the Chinese builder and an army unit stationed near the Great Wall that was to supply engineers for the project. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Xitong </PERSON> listened to both sides at a meeting this month before deciding. He convened the meeting after opponents publicly accused his office of pushing the project through in violation of a 1988 law protecting cultural relics. The cable car was to have been built at Badaling, about 43 miles north of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, where for a few dollars tourists can walk along a small restored section of the Great Wall. Under the cultural relics law, no construction is allowed within 600 feet of the wall at Badaling. The Great Wall, a dramatic symbol of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s historic fear of foreign contact, actually began as a series of short walls built by independent kingdoms and principalities to keep out invaders. Efforts to build one unified wall began about 200 B.C. under <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s first emperor, <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shi </PERSON> <PERSON> Huangdi </PERSON> The completed wall finally stretched 3,700 miles from the desert plains of north-central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to the sea. Large portions are now in ruins. The <ORGANIZATION> Badaling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Glory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> signed a contract to build the cable car a year before the cultural relics law was passed. Golden Glory agreed to invest $ 5 million in the project, with a $ 1.5 million guarantee if it was canceled, the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily said. <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said more than 20 architects and officials from the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and national cultural relics bureaus led the battle against the cable car. They even took the rare step of writing a letter to Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>. Several engineers concluded after a study that the project would lose money. Officials who backed the cable car said it would ease crowding on the wall and thereby prevent damage. Thousands of people visit the wall each day during the tourism season, from about April to October. Tourists currently reach the top via one central set of stairs, then can walk along the wall in both directions for several hundred feet. The wall is about 30 feet high at Badaling.
</TEXT>
