<HEAD>Japan Lifts Sanctions On Chilean Grapes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fruit-Cyanide, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> today lifted a four-day suspension on importing Chilean grapes after <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> pledged to step up safety precautions as a result of a cyanide scare, Japanese officials said. The Japanese government ordered the suspension Tuesday after traces of cyanide were discovered Monday in two Chilean grapes shipped to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The discovery followed anonymous threats to the Japanese and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> that Chilean fruit would be poisoned. The <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> government has reassured <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> it will step up safety precautions to guarantee that grape shipments are safe, leading <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to lift its ban on imports, said <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Katsumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Itoi </PERSON>. The decision comes on the heels of an announcement Friday by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that Chilean fruit exports were once again welcome in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It also comes after the detention Thursday in southern <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> by naval authorities of five Japanese fishing boats `` for safety inspection.'' Chilean navy commander Adm. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> initially said the ships were being held until <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> lifted its ban. But Friday in a telephone interview, Chilean navy Lt. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Araya </PERSON> said, `` The boats are retained and being subject to a mandatory thorough inspection. `` This is necessary for the safety of all people on board those vessels. Once inspectors are satisfied with the safety standards of the boats, they will let them sail off.'' <PERSON> Itoi </PERSON>, asked if the decision to lift <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s ban on Chilean grapes was diplomatically motivated, said: `` The health of the Japanese people is our primary concern.'' There was no immediate word today from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s lifting of the ban. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has imported 1,775 tons of grapes from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> so far this year, representing about 20 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s total imported grapes for the period, according to government figures.
