<HEAD>New Security Measures Imposed After Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with new security measures at
airports. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Adley in...'' TRIMS thereafter to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities have issued new security orders to all major British airports as a result of the December bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103, a <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> spokesman said today. The reported orders came amid criticism by opposition <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> members, who say the government mishandled a warning of a terrorist attack before the disaster, which killed 259 people on board and 11 on the ground in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> refused to confirm any new orders, saying it would not discuss security arrangements. The <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> spokesman, who in keeping with <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> practice refused to be identified, said the orders were received Friday night. He gave no details because they dealt with security matters. British new reports said the directive is believed to require that all passengers be ordered to remove electrical and electronic equipment from suitcases when they check in. They would then carry the items as hand luggage to be examined at boarding gates, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and other news organizations said. Investigators have said the bomb that blew up Flight 103 on Dec. 21 over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, was concealed in a radio-cassette player. The New York-bound flight originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and passengers and luggage changed to a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. On Feb. 18, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> advised all airlines using British airports to begin asking travelers if their baggage contained radios, computers or other electronic equipment and then to examine the items for explosives. Transport Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> was criticized after admitting this week in the wake of newspaper disclosures that authorities were warned terrorists might bomb an aircraft with explosives hidden in a radio-cassette player. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> confirmed Friday that the airline had received a warning from the West German government on Nov. 10 about the kind of radio-cassette bomb that caused the disaster. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> has also acknowledged receiving a warning from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. But it said it received the British warning by mail weeks after the air disaster. <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said this week the British warning contained `` unimportant'' information that supplemented what was in the earlier warnings. A legislator in the governing <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on Friday accused `` hysterical Americans'' of a witch hunt, while party members rallied to fend off opposition charges over the airport security controversy. `` If every government and every airline broadcast every warning from every source _ crank or terrorist _ international air travel would grind to a halt,'' the legislator, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Adley </PERSON>, said Friday. `` The culprit ... is the person who planted the bomb. It is not the -LRB- British -RRB- Secretary of State for Transport.'' <PERSON> Adley </PERSON> in his statement said `` malicious -LRB- opposition -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> politicians, hysterical Americans and news-hungry media'' had united in a `` witch hunt aimed at the Conservative government'' and <PERSON> Channon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Adley </PERSON>, a senior member in the party of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, is an officer of the Conservative legislators' committee on transport. Another Tory legislator, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilshire </PERSON>, said Friday that some relatives of victims have been `` blaming the British government, blaming <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> -LRB- airport -RRB-, blaming anybody except the people I think they ought to be complaining about: namely the American government and <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>.'' In <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, however, the parents of five <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people who died aboard the flight opened a petition drive Friday demanding a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inquiry and accusing <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of treating them in a shoddy manner. `` There is an enormous amount of anger and outrage at the way we've been treated by this country's government,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Primeau </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>. She spoke at a news conference in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Adams </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION> Her 20-year-old twins, <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Coker </PERSON>, who were among the victims.
