<HEAD>China Criticizes Amnesty Petitions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> today condemned recent petitions for the release of political prisoners and sought to discredit the requests as invitations for foreign pressure on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Xinhua commentary was the latest in a series of official statements seeking to quell a growing clamor by Chinese intellectuals for an amnesty for prisoners of conscience and greater freedom of expression. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading dissident, astrophysicist <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, first suggested an amnesty in an open letter to senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> in January. Since then, 118 other intellectuals have signed three similar letters, and hundreds of Chinese studying in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Chinese-Americans, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> and Taiwanese have signed petitions of support. Several delegates are expected to push the idea at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature, which begins its annual session Monday. The strongly worded <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> commentary, with its warning of `` foreign interference,'' appeared to be an effort to head off any public statement at the congress that could embarrass the government. Xinhua accused the letter writers of `` using foreign public opinion to exercise pressure on the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government,'' although no foreign government has officially commented on the amnesty drive. It noted that several of the letters appealed for the release of <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingsheng </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> electrician who was sentenced in 1979 to 15 years in jail for `` counterrevolutionary crimes.'' <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Wei </PERSON>'s case was raised `` not because he is important but because his case aroused much discussion in the foreign press when it became public in 1979.'' The London-based human rights group <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> has championed <PERSON> Wei </PERSON>. `` The Chinese people suffered enough from foreign invasions before the liberation of the country,'' the commentary said. `` Many problems and difficulties do exist, but these are <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s own affairs which the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people will overcome by themselves.''
