<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cargo plane carrying explosives crashed after takeoff from <ORGANIZATION> Carswell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> early today, killing the two people on board and igniting numerous grass fires, authorities said. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Schudt </PERSON> said the two people killed likely were civilians because the DC-9 was a private aircraft under contract to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The victims' identities were not immediately available. `` All of the pastures were on fire,'' said <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON>, a rancher who lives near the ranch where the plane crashed. `` I could see the plane's tires and they were on fire. I told my wife it was a plane crash, then I went to look to see if I could help.'' He drove through burning pastures in his truck but found no survivors. Pentagon spokesman Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundquist </PERSON> said the plane was operated by <ORGANIZATION> Evergreen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, a private contractor based in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. The plane that crashed was based in <LOCATION> Marana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. The plane was en route to <ORGANIZATION> Tinker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> when the crash occurred about 2:30 a.m., said <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Senior Airman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>. A military board will investigate the crash, officials said. He said the cargo included 32 explosive fuses, which weigh a total of about 11 pounds. The plane crashed into a field about seven miles north of the base, which is about seven miles west of downtown <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkey </PERSON>, an investigator for the <ORGANIZATION> Tarrant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said he had been unable to go to the scene because the area was cordoned off until daylight. <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> said the wreckage was scattered over five acres. `` If it had been in a populated area, there would have been more lives lost than two,'' he said. `` It would have destroyed a lot of people and homes.'' The wreckage was almost unrecognizable in predawn light as an airplane except for its large landing wheels and its instrument panels, <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> said.
