<HEAD>Farmers Gather For Congress Of Banned Trade Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes, details of meeting. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To haunting strains of a newly composed hymn, Polish farmers gathered with a sense of vindication today for the first national congress in eight years of their banned union, Rural Solidarity. `` We meet here in a dramatic situation,'' Rural Solidarity chairman <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Slisz </PERSON> said. `` The national economy is destroyed. People in towns and villages live on the edge of poverty. But this is our country. We have to save it for ourselves and our children.'' The congress brought together farmers from every region of the country, plus foreign guests and a visit from <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, chairman of the allied independent workers' union, Solidarity. It took place even before the end of talks between the opposition and communist authorities, which have yielded agreement in principle to legalize Solidarity, Rural Solidarity and the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. All three were banned after martial law was introduced December 1981. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> will consider draft legislation to legalize them again. `` During those eight years, which we spent in prison or in hiding, we did not forget the ideals of Solidarity. Some of our colleagues paid with their lives,'' <PERSON> Slisz </PERSON> said. `` We can meet again after eight years thanks to Mr. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, thanks to his persistence and determination. He is the symbol of Solidarity for cities and villages.'' The hall erupted into chants of `` Solidarnosc! Solidarnosc!'' when <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> appeared. `` My role has been to lead you to this point, so that you can meet and decide about your own activities,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told them. Many farmers had traveled on overnight trains or slept in cars to be on hand for the opening Mass at a modern church on <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s northern outskirts <PERSON> Artur </PERSON> <PERSON> Balazs </PERSON>, a member of Rural Solidarity's national council, said 450 delegates were attending, with 50 invited guests and advisers. They met in a basement hall of the church dominated by a banner proclaiming the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION>, 1981-89. <PERSON> Slisz </PERSON> said the congress must ensure that Rural Solidarity is legalized and prepare for national elections of the union in December. The Rev. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bijak </PERSON> told farmers to draw inspiration for their reborn organization from traditional values that made peasant farmers the backbone of the nation. In a new hymn composed for the congress, an altar assistant then sang, `` <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> lead us to your Son, through our beloved soil.''
</TEXT>
