<FIRST>r i BC-Salvador-Geograph     03-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Salvador-Geograph,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>El Salvador at a Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a look at <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, a nation nestled in the soft <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> curve of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a land with a history of violence that is named for <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 GEOGRAPHY _ The country covers 8,260 square miles, about the size of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. It is rugged, a land of volcanoes and lakes and rich soil. It is about 950 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, 950 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 POPULATION _ Its more than 5 million people are mainly Roman Catholic and mestizo _ people of both <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> heritage. More than 500,000 of its residents have fled its 9-year-old civil war, most of them to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 HISTORY _ It was conquered in 1525 by the Spanish. It became independent on Sept. 15, 1821 and joined the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, which later split into the nations that now make up <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It was ruled for most of this century by a land-owning oligarchy in alliance with the military. In 1932 a peasant rebellion organized by <PERSON> Farabundo </PERSON> <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> was crushed by a military regime that killed 30,000 people; the leader of that rebellion inspired the present guerrillas, the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 ECONOMY _ It is mostly agricultural, with coffee the main cash crop. In the 1960s and 1970s it became a manufacturing center for the Central American market. Its largest input is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military and civil aid, which comes to $ 1.5 million a day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE WAR _ The conflict began in 1979 when a group of young officers overthrew then-president Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON>. A junta tried to impose agrarian and social reforms, but dissatisfied leftists began a rebellion in late 1979. The conflict has led to more than 70,000 deaths, most of them civilian, many of them suspected leftists killed by right-wing death squads in the early 1980s. In 1984, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, a Christian Democrat, became the first popularly elected president in 50 years. Sunday's election marks the first time Salvadorans have had a chance to replace an incumbent civilian government with a different party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
