<HEAD>Crowds Stream Into Shuttle Viewing Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with crowd singing as shuttle lands,
new quotes, other details from scene; Picks up 3rd graf, `Many of ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shuttle Landing, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto EA81</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shuttle watchers who arrived in a parade of flag-bedecked motorhomes cheered, sang and cried with pride today as the winged spacecraft Discovery returned home. As the shuttle touched down the flag-waving crowd estimated at 450,000 broke into applause and spontaneously sang the national anthem. Tears streamed from the eyes of some, while others among the crowd hugged their children. Most snapped pictures furiously, marveling at the shuttle's steep angle of descent. `` I'm just fascinated by it,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dube </PERSON>, 34, of Canyon Country, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dube </PERSON> was one of hundreds poised for a quick getaway, and was on the road right after the shuttle landed at 6:36 a.m. to avoid a massive jam that soon stacked up on the <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> public viewing site Authorities estimated 138,000 vehicles were on hand. `` It's Saturday, if it was a work day I'd hang around a little longer,'' he said. As many as 300 motorists who arrived after roads to the base were closed simply pulled their vehicles off the highway and drove onto the desert to watch the landing. Several motorists ran into trouble, however, damaging their vehicles' axles when they drove into large desert potholes. Today's crowd of 450,000 was the second-largest to witness a shuttle landing. The record number was 500,000 for the shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s July 4, 1982, landing. Many of the motor homes jamming the two-lane road leading toward <LOCATION> Rogers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, where crowds began gathering earlier this week, sported huge <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags. `` The patriotic spirit here is really something,'' said <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, 70, of Garden Grove. `` I even bought a new flag for this.'' Throngs of people, some arriving by motorcycle, others in cars pulling travel trailers, arrived several days early to claim the best viewing spots. On Friday, the strains of country music blared over loudspeakers at the makeshift campground as military helicopters buzzed overhead and skateboarders rattled across the hardened lake bed. Dune buggies and other off-road vehicles filled the area five miles from the <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> landing site with clouds of dust. <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, who arrived Wednesday, said he was on hand when the shuttle Atlantis landed last year. `` It was really worth it. It raises the hair on your back when you hear those sonic booms. Teardrops fall and the whole thing,'' he said. Many of the early arrivals were so-called `` snowbirds,'' retired couples who spend their winters in warm climates. `` We winter in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> every year and we just had to see the shuttle land,'' said 74-year-old <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sunnyside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, who arrived with his wife, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON>. `` I'm sure we'd see it better on TV, but we just had to be here,'' he said. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolner </PERSON>, 35, a nurse from <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, witnessed the shuttle lift off Monday in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` My husband wanted to know what I wanted for Christmas and I told him I wanted to see the shuttle take off,'' she said. `` I spent the night in the car and watched it take off, and when I got home I told him I wanted to see it land. I flew to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Wednesday. I rented a car and here I am.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Tolner </PERSON> was quickly adopted by a family in a motorhome and was celebrating with the rest of the crowd. `` Everyone has such a sense of pride and respect,'' she said.
