<HEAD>Congress Becoming Restive over Salvador Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> has been receiving a huge slice of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid program for years but now, as <LOCATION> Salvadorans </LOCATION> prepare to elect a new president, many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> feel <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayers have not been getting their money's worth. The Salvadoran war still rages, having claimed an estimated 70,000 lives, the economy is stagnant and politically-motivated killings are up, prompting some lawmakers to argue for a major policy shift regardless of who the next Salvadoran president is. The pressure for a new approach is expected to accelerate if, as expected, the candidate of the rightist ARENA party, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, wins the election outright on Sunday or the subsequent runoff. His principal opponent is Christian Democrat <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON>. Despite <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s denials, the perception among many who count in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is that ARENA is tied to the death squads _ shadowy groups who target both real and suspected leftists, sometimes in cooperation with the military. Perception plays a key role in forming opinions on administration policy. Democrats tend to be outraged by figures that show an average of 20 political killings a month recently while Republicans note that such incidents once averaged 800 a month. Still, the situation was serious enough to warrant a forceful appeal last month by Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> to the Salvadoran military `` to work toward the elimination of human rights violations.'' The administration also is worried that <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> might become a strategic headache for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> rebels triumph. The <O