d pending a presidential report on progress toward prosecution of human rights offenders and toward ending the war and death squad activity. The program for the current year calls for $ 292.5 in economic aid and $ 96.5 in military aid. Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations, told Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> on Wednesday he believes the administration should emphasize political and diplomatic measures to end <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s civil war `` I think up till now we've tried to implement primarily a military track and it's failed,'' he said. `` I ca n't support more aid with no strings attached without significant changes in our whole approach to that country.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> strongly defended the Salvadoran government's approach to the conflict, pointing out that the army has unilaterally declared a cease-fire to last through June 1. In addition, five relatively free elections have been held since 1982 and <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> has made a number of efforts to negotiate an end to the war, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, the rebels `` are doing whatever they can to disrupt the election'' despite their stated desire for peace, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> predicted the rebel tactics will fail. `` We condemn <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> violence and applaud the efforts of ordinary Salvadorans to establish firmly democratic rule in their troubled country. The elections on Sunday will be the next step to achieving that goal,'' he said.
