<TEXT>
 For one night at the <ORGANIZATION> Subs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> bar, everything was on the house _ even much of the house itself. A brash manager, without the owner's permission, apparently gave away $ 2,000 worth of liquor, beer and wine, police reported. He also gave away or sold tables, chairs, glasses, a television set and 15 neon beer signs. The cash register also went. The manager apparently pocketed any money made on the sales, police said. `` Apparently their liquor license was expiring and they were going to close shop,'' police investigator <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Falls </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. `` The manager may have just taken advantage of the situation. He apparently decided to just go ahead and give everything away.'' The bar's owner, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Garland </LOCATION>, discovered the loss when he arrived about 7:30 p.m. Thursday. Several patrons told him that the manager told people in the bar at 5 p.m. that they could have anything they wanted on the house. Falls said he tracked down one woman who got in on the windfall happy hour. `` She said he was handing things away right and left and that she had got a bottle of liquor,'' Falls said. Falls said the manager could be arrested and charged with theft once police make certain that he held no ownership stake in the club.
