<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Young Soviet women will soon be able to discard their unstylish clothes and for the first time buy the same trendy fashions as their European and American counterparts. Three European companies are finalizing joint-ventures they believe will revolutionize Soviet fashion by offering Soviet women the Western styles they can now get only from friends traveling abroad, foreign currency stores or the black market. The deals will put branches of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Coppernob chain and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stefanel </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> chains _ which all cater to the youth market _ in cities across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Soviet women will get their first chance to buy Western clothes by the end of March when <ORGANIZATION> Stefanel </ORGANIZATION> expects to open two stores in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON>, an account executive for <ORGANIZATION> Stefanel </ORGANIZATION>'s public relations firm, said Friday in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Under a joint venture contract with the city of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> signed in September, he said, one store will accept the Soviet ruble and the other dollars, which tourists and limited numbers of Soviets have access to. American-born designer <PERSON> Gifi </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON>, whose Coppernob clothes are sold in more than 50 British stores, said Friday he expects to open four or five stores in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> this fall _ all accepting rubles. He also expects to open a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> factory by the end of the year to assemble partly made clothes imported from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> <PERSON> Verengo </PERSON>, said the company has been negotiating an agreement with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government that would allow them to open about 50 stores in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> cities and build two or three factories to produce <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> clothes for the Soviet market. He said the agreement was likely to be signed this year. Fields credited Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s desire to reform the Soviet economy and meet the growing demand for consumer goods for the decision to allow Western clothing firms into the country for the first time. The joint ventures, he said, offer `` a historic opportunity'' to bring the Soviet people closer to their European neighbors with whom they share a similar culture and taste in clothes. `` Obviously there's a great potential in a market which is basically dealing in total functional clothing with no flair,'' said Fields, 37, in an interview. He said London-based Coppernob has reached agreement in principle with two <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> cooperatives, <PERSON> Nevski </PERSON> <PERSON> Zori </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lilia </PERSON>, to open the factory and branches throughout the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Details of the accord, reached during a trip to <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> in February, were being finalized. Under the deal, he said, <PERSON> Coppernob </PERSON> will invest any profits in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He did not say how much <PERSON> Coppernob </PERSON> would invest in the project. `` Initially we're starting the operation off as small,'' he said. `` I can see us in 10 years time producing mega-amounts of fashion clothing in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> not only for the marketplace in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but to service the rest of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and possibly even the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The clothes going on sale in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> this fall will be virtually the same as the clothes he'll be selling in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ lots of wool tweed jackets with short skirts or jeans, rich corduroys and stylish but simple velvet dresses. `` Good young fashion is like music, it transcends all boundaries,'' Fields said.
