<HEAD>Show from Museum in Britain Opens at National Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 400 years ago a young man about <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> apparently tried to start what would now be called a punk fashion: he took to wearing his blonde hair long over his left shoulder but short on the other side. The fashion failed to catch on but the young man, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wriothesly </PERSON>, Third Earl of <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION>, is remembered anyhow. Many authorities believe <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> was writing his sonnets at the time _ 1594 _ in support of a family effort to make the 20-year-old earl get married and produce an heir. <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> wrote two longer poems for him, one with a dedication evidencing as much friendship as was socially acceptable at that period between a mere playwright and a nobleman. A tiny oval portrait of <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION>, showing the unsuccessful `` lovelock,'' is a feature of a show of `` Treasures from the <LOCATION> Fitzwilliam </LOCATION>,'' the museum of <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, opening Sunday at the National Gallery of Art. `` The <LOCATION> Fitzwilliam </LOCATION> is perhaps <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s pre-eminent small museum,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, director of the National Gallery. The painting is by <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilliard </PERSON>, the most famous miniaturist of the period. Only about an inch and a half in height, it was done on the back of a calfskin playing card. Three hearts can still be seen on the other side. <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION> did get marrieda few years later, after a scandalous affair with a lady in waiting to Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>. He had been a favorite of the queen and later she commuted a death sentence against him for taking part in a conspiracy against her. He died on a military expedition to the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> in 1624. The exhibition includes more than 160 objects from the <LOCATION> Fitzwilliam </LOCATION>. They range from a bit of soft-core pornography by the 18th century British satirist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogarth </PERSON> to a portrait by Sir <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyck </PERSON> of <PERSON> Arhcbishop </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Laud </PERSON> _ a strict and highly dignified churchman who helped get King Charles I into a lot of political trouble 100 years before. Both Laud and the king were beheaded. There are also a little water spaniel in painted porcelain and assorted coins, drawings, furniture, manuscripts and bronzes. The most famous painting is one by <PERSON> Titian </PERSON> that by coincidence deals with the same subject as <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s poem to <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION> with the friendly dedication, `` The Rape of Lucrece.'' The picture was painted in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, about 25 years before <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> wrote the poem. The exhibition will be at the gallery's East Building through June 18. Then it goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Kimbell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, July 15 to Oct. 8; the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Nov. 5 to Jan. 28, 1990; the <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, Feb. 20 to May 6, 1990 and the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>, June 21 to Sept. 9, 1990.
