<HEAD>Prison Furlough Programs Provide Some Rewards and Considerable Risk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The case of an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> inmate charged with murdering his former wife during a brief prison furlough reflects rising concern in many states for striking the right balance between rehabilitation and public safety. Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> suspended the furlough program that released <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> hours before <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>, 29, was beaten to death March 4 outside her northern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> home. <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> says the program may never be restored and directed seven prison officials to face disciplinary hearings. Most state prisons allow limited inmate furloughs, brief periods of freedom ranging from a few hours to a week when prisoners can look for a job, visit a relative, get a medical exam or attend a funeral. Thousands of other prisoners work day jobs and return to prison at night. `` These people are going to get out eventually,'' says <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> prisons spokeswoman <PERSON> Iris </PERSON> <PERSON> Crumbly </PERSON>. `` We're preparing them, easing them out, getting them re-acclimated to living in the community.'' A furlough can be a payoff, too, for an inmate who does n't make trouble. `` It's a reward for good behavior and adherence to discipline,'' says <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Archibald </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s prison department. A few states, such as <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, do n't allow furloughs or work release. Other states, including <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, have turned to extended furloughs and early release to relieve prison overcrowding. The system appears to work smoothly, most of the time. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> runs an extensive furlough program, granting 5,658 work-release permits and 14 compassionate furloughs last September alone. Only one inmate failed to return. Missouri reports 99.9 percent of inmates furloughed in 1988 obeyed the rules and committed no new crimes. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> has become only the latest in a growing number of states, however, that are tightening the rules on furloughs, or eliminating some programs entirely. Even the very few failures may shatter public confidence, threaten political careers and end lives. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, the furloughed <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> inmate who terrorized a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> couple and became a political battering ram in <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidential campaign against <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, is merely the best-known of those failures. There are others: _ In the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> case, <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON>, 38, had been sentenced to eight years for beating Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> in 1987, two years after their divorce, and she had become a counselor and advocate for battered women Prison officials knew of <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON>'s continued hostility toward her, but failed to warn Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>, as promised, of his release. In an interview videotaped by prosecutors two years ago, a badly bruised Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> said <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> had threatened to `` make my life so miserable that I would wish daily that I was dead.'' `` I bartered for my life yesterday and told him that I would not prosecute,'' she continued. `` I'm afraid if he does get ahold of me again that I'm not going to be able to talk about it.'' <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> will face the death sentence if convicted. _ In <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, prison trusty <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> was charged with shooting to death his girlfriend during a weekend release in August 1988 <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> was serving a life sentence for killing his wife in 1982. _ In <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, businesswoman <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballasiotes </PERSON> was slain last September by work-release inmate <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, whom psychiatrists had described years earlier as a sexual psychopath, was sentenced to life without _ In <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, a judge gave <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Beets </PERSON>, 29, a 48-hour furlough from a trespass and battery jail sentence to attend the funeral of an aunt Beets now is charged in the March 10 hammering death of <PERSON> Oretha </PERSON> <PERSON> Hames </PERSON>, 71, and the attempted murder of her daughter _ Beets' girlfriend _ <PERSON> Vanita </PERSON> <PERSON> Hames </PERSON>, 28 `` Should I punish everyone in the future because this man did something horrible?'' asked Las Vegas Municipal Judge <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who granted the furlough. `` It was a kindness to -LRB- Beets' -RRB- family that turned into a nightmare.'' Prison officials say inmates are carefully screened before furloughs are granted. But murderers are eligible in several states, including <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> rapist won work release and was charged again with rape. A <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> murderer was granted weekend passes, although rules forbade it. Even inmates with clean prison records can be unpredictable. `` After all, they are prisoners,'' says <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> prison spokesman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Massie </PERSON>. `` They have been convicted of crimes against society.'' Some states have clamped down on furloughs and early releases after well-publicized crimes, while others have taken similar steps to avoid borrowing trouble. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> tightened furlough rules after the 1987 <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> case, choosing not to eliminate either that program or work release. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> implemented tougher policies since <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> was charged. The new standards would have kept <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, who won an exception because he was assigned to the governor's mansion, under guard. The old policy treated furloughs `` as some kind of reward for service within the institution,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. `` To me, that's not valid.'' <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Patuxent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, a psychiatric center, came under criticism when it was revealed one triple murderer had regular furloughs, and a convicted rapist was charged with rape while on work release. Patuxent suspended all furlough and work-release programs in November. Five years ago, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> sharply cut furloughs after two furloughed inmates were charged with a series of rapes in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> Circuit Attorney <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Peach </PERSON>, a critic of the program, says he still worries, despite more stringent regulations. `` All I can say is that we have n't recently had a front-page story of a furlough guy committing a crime,'' Peach says. `` I think that's probably luck.''
