<HEAD>Syrians Erect New Gun Positions In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian soldiers set up mortars and rocket launchers on rooftops in the Moslem sector Saturday after the commander of the Christian army vowed to drive the Syrian army out of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Sporadic artillery fire resounded across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Saturday as Syrian-backed Druse gunners fired into the state-run <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> and Christian residential neigborhoods near the city's dividing Green Line. Police said three people were wounded. The hostilities violated a cease-fire called Thursday to give mediators a chance to end fighting that began 10 days ago, killing 49 people and wounding 164, by police count. The truce was to expire at midnight Saturday. The fighting between Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> forces began after Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, the commander of the Christian army, blockaded illegal ports used by Moslem militias to import supplies. The Syrians on Saturday deployed mortars and rocket launchers atop high-rise apartment buildings in outlying residential districts of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the Shiite Moslem southern slums. They apparently were preparing for a resumption of the fighting when the truce ends. The Syrians maintain a 12,000-strong contingent in west and south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, part of 40,000 troops stationed in north, east and central <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. Reliable witnesses, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Syrians also were digging artillery gun pits and foxholes and erecting new sandbag positions in and around the southern suburbs. `` You should not panic,'' one Syrian officer told a visibly worried resident while the reinforcements were being brought in. `` We're not going to start any fighting. We are here to protect you.'' However, hundreds of Shiite residents were seen packing luggage, beds and mattresses, and leaving the slums on the outskirts of the capital in cars heading for south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials, who requested anonymity, said more than 8,000 Shiites from <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> have taken refuge with relatives living in areas policed by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping forces. `` We do not need a guardian who claims he is protecting us ... while in reality he is killing us, sponging away our wealth and usurping our sovereignty,'' <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> said Friday. `` Our option is liberation. We shall fight and use every other means to bring about the <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> withdrawal,'' said <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, 53, a Maronite Catholic who commands 20,000 mostly Christian troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s fractured army. His remark was criticized by acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, a pro-Syrian official who heads the mainly Moslem cabinet competing for legitimacy with the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> military cabinet under <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>. `` You are planting war but you are not going to reap any liberation,'' said <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem. `` The Syrians are here at the request of legitimate authorities, and their departure can be decided only by a united cabinet.'' Their remarks appeared to dim the chances of an agreement to resolve the latest round of fighting in the 14-year-old civil war.
