<FIRST>r i AM-China-Congress     03-18 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Congress,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>National People's Congress Opens Monday, Fight Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature opens its annual meeting Monday, and some observers expect a tough fight between delegates calling for democratic change and government officials stressing stability. The government argues that it needs stability to solve <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s pressing economic problems Many intellectuals say the economic problems will persist unless the government relaxes tight political controls. Pro-democratic forces are expected to continue an open-letter campaign, urging an amnesty for political prisoners and respect for human rights. Since January, four such letters have been sent, signed by more than 100 leading intellectuals. The last letter was sent last week, despite threats of punishment by government officials. Delegates also said they expected the issue of human rights to be raised at the congress itself, an unprecedented act of defiance. `` It will be a lively time,'' said one Communist Party member. `` Intellectuals will push as far as they can go.'' Government officials have ordered the state-run media to censor reports of disagreements at the 2,796-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and portray the delegates as united, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> sources said And the restrictions are apparently not limited to the domestic press. On Friday night, Chinese authorites interrogated two Taiwanese journalists after they had interviewed a delegate. Two teams of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> reporters were also stopped from talking with delegates. <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhichao </PERSON>, a government spokesman, apologized for the incidents, but he said he could not assure it would not happen again. `` It will be a step back from last year,'' said one delegate. During last year's congress, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> news media was allowed to report some disagreements between delegates as part of the state's attempt at openness. The government has been emphasizing that it needs stability to solve <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s weighty economic problems. By doing so, party sources said, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> hopes to persuade wavering delegates that it's best to remain quiet and follow the government line. In an attempt at conciliation, the government has announced it will appoint more members of democratic parties to government positions. The first appointments were made Friday when <ORGANIZATION> non-Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members were appointed vice-minister of labor and vice-minister of agriculture. Delegates said the appointments will be made to present an image of democracy and to take some of the blame off the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for failed policies. `` But it will fail,'' said one party member. `` All the delegates know that the ` democratic' parties are even more communist than the Communist Party.'' The congress is also expected to pass some laws, two of which are critical to the reform of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s political system. One law gives civilians the right to sue the government. It has been criticized by liberal thinkers because it does not acknowledge that the government can break the law. But moderates have hailed it as a step in the right direction. Another law delineates the powers of the congress, an important step in reforms designed to separate the functions of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> from the government. The congress opens against a backdrop of serious political and economic problems. Inflation is running at a record 36 percent. Grain harvests have been below target for the past five years. Electricity is in scarce supply. Steel production has dropped. Salt and cotton are hard to buy. Corruption among government officials and party members appears at an all time high. Newspapers are filled with reports of official malfeasance.
