<HEAD>Chile Resumes Fruit Exports, Braces for Economic Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Troops stood guard Saturday as <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> resumed fruit exports after a poisoning scare caused a five-day stoppage that idled thousands of workers and may cost the nation up to $ 1 billion, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Urbina </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Valparaiso </LOCATION> port, said two ships were being loaded with 700,000 crates of grapes, apples, pears and kiwis. He said navy troops were deployed around the clock to watch over the shipments and access to the port was tightly controlled. Twelve more ships were to be loaded over the weekend, the officer said. The shipments ended a public health scare that began Monday when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health officials said they found traces of cyanide on two Chilean grapes in the port of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. But on Friday, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lifted consumer warnings on Chilean produce, announcing tougher security measures. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, which had issued similar warnings, followed suit. Chilean authorities said economic effects of the virtual embargo would be felt for years to come. The industry, which employs 500,000 workers and accounts for 10 percent of the nation's exports, may lose up to $ 1 billion, government officials said. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Feliu </PERSON>, president of the nation's largest business association, said <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> had already lost $ 200 million, while authorities said 200,000 fruit industry workers were laid off. The government on Friday announced economic measures to combat the crisis, including a subsidized advertising campaign in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> designed to regain consumer confidence. Other measures included a $ 12 million emergency job program, emergency credit lines to fruit exporters and producers and the purchase of 1 million crates of stocked fruit. Under new security measures taking effect Monday, army patrols were to be posted in fruit fields and at packing houses and police were to step up security checks on trucks carrying produce to ports, <PERSON> Urbina </PERSON> said. Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> also were to join Chilean colleagues in reinforcing sanitary controls in ports and fruit packing plants. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, health officials were to step up spot checks of Chilean produce. Initial checks of Chilean fruit were made after embassies in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> received anonymous threats that fruit from the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nation would be poisoned. The government attributed the calls to leftist terrorists.
