<HEAD>Protesters Say Hunters Slaughtering Even More Seals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hundred animal lovers demonstrated Saturday against the slaughter of baby seals off <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>'s north coast, saying it is worse now than when it was made illegal in 1982. Hunters have shifted their sights to pups older than nine days since the 1982 legislation prohibited killing of `` white coats'' _ seals under that age, said a spokesman for demonstrators from <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, who marched peacefully around <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> building. `` That makes it even worse,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Best </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> that organized the protest. `` Where the ` white coats' were taken on the pan ice around the north shore of <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> and just about all that were killed were harvested, the hunt now is mainly at sea where it's estimated three pups have to be killed for every one got into the boats. `` Now it's on the open seas where it is almost impossible to regulate. There are n't any inspectors or scientists out there. Nobody knows what's going on,'' he said. The harvest, which bottomed out at 20,000 seals a year right after the legislation was enacted, since has risen to 80,000, <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> said. He also said the government issues 9,000 licenses a season to hunt seals, compared to 5,000 before the legislation. The government quota for this season is 186,000 harp seals and 2,340 hooded seals, he said. `` We thought we had won in 1982, and so did everyone else,'' Best recalls. `` But we did n't win; we lost. Now we've got to start all over again.''
</TEXT>
