<TEXT>
 Disclosures of detailed warnings in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> before the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> have prompted calls for new investigations and appeals for more government openness about terrorist threats. A congressional subcommittee analysis of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> security warnings, due for release Sunday, will show that many <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> warnings are `` woefully inadequate,'' according to a committee staff member. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> dispatched top aides to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> this weekend to examine the growing controversy over the warnings and to determine the safety of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines from terrorist attack. And, some of the relatives of the 270 people killed in the Dec. 21 disaster planned a White House protest April 3, the 103rd day after the bombing. <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, the brother of one of those killed, pleaded: `` I'd like the opportunity to make my own decison on whether I die on a plane or not. The latest actions follow revelations and discussions in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> about very specific warnings that airlines and government officials were sharing in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the weeks before the bombing over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. None of the information got to passengers. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, after it did warn passengers of a bomb threat against a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-Paris </LOCATION> flight last week, said it has a long-standing policy of advising travelers and giving them the option of taking other flights when there is a specific threat against an individual flight. The <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> disaster was not preceded by any reported threat that named a specific plane. But disclosures over the past several weeks indicate that authorities had several other warnings, including what airline and flights might be endangered, in what month the bombing could occur, what type of explosive and triggering device might be used and even how the bomb might be concealed in a radio-cassette. Investigators concluded that a radio-cassette containing plastic explosives set to go off at a certain altitude blew up <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103. Both British aviation authorities and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> had described a radio-cassette bomb in security warnings a month earlier, after one was confiscated in a raid in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on the Syrian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> acknowledges that it received a warning about such a device from the West German government on Nov. 10. Various other warnings that have elements similar to what occurred in the Pan Am bombing also were issued Dec. 5 to all airlines, Dec. 13 to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies, Nov. 17 to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines, Nov. 22 to British airlines and Dec. 19 to British airports and several airlines. Some of the warnings, including the final one two days before the bombing, were not received for several days. Although investigators apparently have focused much of their attention on the Palestinian guerrilla group which was the subject of some of the warnings, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials said Friday that contrary to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> press reports, they had not captured or identified any suspected bomber. On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, where several committees have been examining issues raised by the destruction of Flight 103, House Government Operations subcommittee staff members were compiling 27 <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> security warnings issued in 1988 and another four this year, most of them not made public. The subcommittee planned to look into how each one was handled, who was warned, when they were warned, and how the government and airlines dealt with the threats, a subcommitee source said, discussing the report on condition of anonymity. `` We are looking at their accuracy, timeliness and usefulness,'' the source said. The report is to focus particularly on the Nov. 17 warning dealing with a radio-cassette bomb. The source said subcommittee chairwoman Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., decided to conduct the analysis because there of confusion about the warnings and a host of complaints from victims' relatives and others <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> high school administrator who was one of about 20 victims' relatives who met with <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, said the families are calling for a ban on all batteries on airliners, because plastic explosives can not be set off without a battery. The group also wants a system set up so passengers can call a number and find out about any threats, more efforts to match luggage with passengers and routine questioning of passengers as they board flights. `` At best, this has been handled in a chaotic way,'' said <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, whose brother <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> was killed in the bombing. `` At worst, there's been a coverup.''
