12 inches of snow fell Friday and early Saturday across parts of the area. `` It's been awful, awful,'' said <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> State Police Sgt. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Ignaczak </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, where at least 100 traffic accidents, one a 20-car chain collision, were reported between 2 a.m. and 11 a.m. Saturday. No serious injuries were reported. In the West, a cold front spread rain over northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region and snow fell at higher elevations of northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. Up to 10 inches of snow blanketed the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> overnight, with 12 inches reported at <LOCATION> Chester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Up to two feet of snow was expected in the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> area by Sunday morning, along with up to 3 feet of snow in the neighboring <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> range Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9 degrees above zero at <LOCATION> Warroad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, to 89 at <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Saturday's low for the Lower 48 states was 16 below zero at <LOCATION> Warroad </LOCATION>. For Sunday, scattered showers were forecast from the northern and central <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> across <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, with snow over northwestern <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and western and central Montana. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast across <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and southern and central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Widely scattered rain and snow showers wer