<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-Viewing     03-18 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Viewing,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Patriotic Cheers, Tears _ And a Monumental Traffic Jam</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flags waved, tears of pride flowed and a spontaneous rendition of the national anthem broke out in the desert dawn Saturday among the 450,000 people who watched the return of the space shuttle Discovery. `` I'm just fascinated by it,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dube </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Country </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a veteran of the temporary encampments that spring up on <LOCATION> Rogers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> here for landings of the winged spacecraft. The crowd, many of whom arrived earlier in the week, burst out in whistles and cheers at the thump of two sonic booms that preceded Discovery's arrival over this <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> base 60 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. About two minutes later the ship appeared, seemingly straight overhead, as a speck glinting in the dawn sunlight. Most lapsed into surprised silence at the shuttle's steep descent, but the celebration resumed as Discovery landed on a strip about five miles distant at 6:35 a.m. PST. Spectators clapped, whooped, snapped pictures and waved <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags. Many spontaneously began singing the national anthem. Some cried; others hugged their children. `` The patriotic spirit here is really something,'' said <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, 70, of <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, who flew a flag atop a telescoping 60-foot pole. `` I even bought a new flag for this.'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials estimated the crowd at the public viewing area at 450,000, and said an additional 10,000 watched at the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> facility. That was second only to the 500,000 who joined President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to watch shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s July 4, 1982, landing. Shortly after landing, the estimated 138,000 motorhomes, cars and trucks jammed the two narrow, one-lane blacktop roads that led to the nearest highway, 30 miles from the vewing site. Remembering the five-hour traffic jam that followed the last landing, <PERSON> Dube </PERSON> was one of hundreds poised for a quick getaway, and was on the road right after the shuttle touched down. `` It's Saturday. If it was a work day I'd hang around a little longer,'' he said. Spectators began gathering earlier in the week to stake out prime viewing spots. The came in flag-bedecked motorhomes, aboard motorcycles, and in cars pulling travel trailers. As many as 300 people who arrived after roads to the base were closed simply pulled off the highway and drove onto the desert to watch the landing. Several got stuck or damaged their axles when they accidentally drove into holes in the desert hardpan. On Friday, the strains of country music blared over loudspeakers at the makeshift campground as military helicopters buzzed overhead and skateboarders rattled across the hardened lake bed. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolner </PERSON>, 35, a nurse from <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, witnessed the shuttle lift off Monday in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` My husband wanted to know what I wanted for Christmas and I told him I wanted to see the shuttle take off,'' she said. `` I spent the night in the car and watched it take off, and when I got home I told him I wanted to see it land. I flew to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Wednesday. I rented a car and here I am.'' Many of the early arrivals were so-called `` snowbirds,'' retired couples who spend their winters in warm climates. `` We winter in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> every year and we just had to see the shuttle land,'' said 74-year-old <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sunnyside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, who arrived with his wife, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON>. `` I'm sure we'd see it better on TV, but we just had to be here,'' he said.
