<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Leaders Seek To Unify Soweto and Johannesburg</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-apartheid leaders in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> say a prolonged rent boycott is likely to continue until the vast black township is unified economically and politically with neighboring <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. A committee of activists, including Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, concluded in a new report that <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> will never be able to pay off a $ 300 million debt accumulated since most families stopped paying rent and service charges in 1986. The committee is urging the white-controlled government to write off the debt and create a single tax base for <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> so money spent by blacks in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> can be returned to their own community for development and services. `` No development policy for <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> will succeed until <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> are treated as one urban economy,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, chairman of the seven-member committee, at a news conference Thursday. <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general-secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, said the proposal represents a fundamental challenge to apartheid because a unified economy would entail a unified political entity. `` The demand is actually for a normal country with normal cities,'' he said. `` The system must be deracialized.'' An estimated 2.5 million blacks live in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, the country's largest municipality The white population of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and its adjacent suburbs is about 600,000. The rent boycott, launched to press grievances against the government, has evolved into one of the most effective forms of protest available to blacks under the 33-month-old state of emergency. Authorites have used numerous tactics in futile attempts to break the boycott, including late-night eviction raids such as one in August 1986 that led to the deaths of nearly 30 blacks in a clash with police. <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>'s committee said the <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> town council should write off rental arrears owed by householders, implement affordable service charges, and establish a formula for transferring ownership of rented homes to long-term occupants. A study released by the committee said Sowetans spend $ 400 million annually in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, generating tax revenue that benefits white residents without returning to <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. According to the study, businesses provide about 70 percent of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s tax revenue, enabling white homeowners to pay lower service fees than Sowetans yet get better services. Compared to <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> has only a handful of licensed businesses. The most common businesses in the township are unlicensed grocery stores and pubs which pay no taxes. <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>'s committee already has met with the <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> town council and hopes to arrange a further meeting. The activists also want to confer with the <ORGANIZATION> Johannesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> mayor, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkhwanazi </PERSON> has surprised the activists by acknowledging their influence in the community. The committee includes the general-secretary of the black miners' union, <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramaphosa </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Albertina </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, wife of jailed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>.
