<HEAD>Britain Issues New Security Orders to its Carriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New security orders have been issued to all of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s major airports, a <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION> airport spokesman said Saturday. The orders came amid controversy over warnings received before the December bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103. The British news media said it was believed the new directive requires passengers to remove all electric and electronic equipment from luggage before check-in and to pack such items in hand luggage to be examined at boarding gates. Investigators have said the bomb that blew up Flight 103 on Dec. 21 over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, killing all 259 people on the plane and 11 on the ground, was concealed in a radio-cassette player. A Manchester airport spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British practice, said the orders were received Friday night but he could not give details because it was a security matter. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> would not say if a new directive had been sent. But it reaffirmed a Feb. 18 message that advised all airlines using British airports to begin asking travelers if their baggage contained radios, computers or such equipment and then to examine the items for possible explosives. The message did not say if examined items should be carried as hand baggage or be checked through with other luggage. The <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> came under renewed attack Saturday for its handling of a bomb warning before Flight 103 blew up. It was disclosed Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had prepared a warning dated Dec. 19 that included photographs of a bomb disguised in a radio-cassette player, but it did not mail the advisory until after Christmas. Transport Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said the advice was of little importance because similar information had been disseminated a month earlier by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Flight 103 originated in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and changed planes at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airport before departing for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Early editions of two Sunday newspapers, The Observer and The Sunday Telegraph, said the Dec. 19 warning carried several details that would have helped security people spot a rigged radio-cassette player. The Sunday Telegraph quoted <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> as saying, `` Yes, maybe the security information contained in the December 19 letter should have been sent out by telex. The reason this was not done was because the crucial element of the message consisted of a color photograph of a possible explosive device.'' The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday repeated its request for an independent inquiry into the Flight 103 disaster. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s transport spokesman, said <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> had caused `` muddle and confusion'' over the issue of warnings. `` The relatives of those who died in the <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> disaster have the right to expect a full and open account of how the government responded from the moment it received the warnings of a possible terrorist attack,'' he said. <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> responded by saying <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> was using the situation `` to try and make party political points of the worst possible kind, preying on the grief of bereaved people. `` We're trying to get to the bottom of this,'' <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said on a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> broadcast. Conservative legislator <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Adley </PERSON> on Friday replied to criticism from the opposition and from families of the victims. He said `` malicious Labor politicians, hysterical Americans and news-hungry media'' had united in a `` witch hunt aimed at the Conservative government in general and the secretary of state for transport in particular.''
