<HEAD>GAF Jury Deadlocked in Wall Street Fraud Case Tied To Boesky</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: DELETES extraneous 15th graf, `The purpose ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first criminal trial stemming from Wall Street's insider trading scandals faced the prospect of a second mistrial when a jury on Saturday reported an 11-1 deadlock after eight days of deliberations. A federal judge asked jurors in the <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock manipulation case to reconsider all evidence after they reported the split following more than 65 hours of deliberations. The <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> case is the first trial based on the confessions of insider trader <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, which led to the indictment, and is considered a test of the government's ability to try Wall Street corruption. `` Your honor. We need help. There are 11 jurors who have come to a unanimous decision on counts one through eight and one juror who does not agree,'' the jury reported in a note read in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. The panel reported that the juror said `` under no circumstances'' could he agree with the other jurors' decision. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>, two subsidiaries and Vice Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> are charged with allegedly trying to boost the stock price of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 shortly before selling a large block of shares. They also were charged with securities fraud, wire fraud and conspiracy among the eight counts. Under an instruction known as the <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> charge, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> asked the jurors to reconsider their positions in the securities fraud case and sent them back to deliberate. `` Before I declare a mistrial and discharge you I want to point out a few things to you,'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said. `` It is desirable that if a verdict can be reached that this be done.'' But <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> told the jury that they should not reverse positions solely to reach a verdict and left resolution to the `` conscientious judgment of each juror.'' After hearing the judge's statement, the jury said it wanted to continue deliberating Sunday afternoon. The point of conflict among the jurors and whether the 11 supported acquittal or conviction were not known. A mistrial would be the second in the case. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> declared a mistrial Jan. 10 after ruling that the prosecution unintentionally withheld a key piece of evidence. The second trial lasted six weeks. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>, N.J.-based chemical and building materials manufacturer, faces a maximum fine of $ 12 million, or $ 500,000 on each of the eight counts. <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>, 55, of <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, faces 40 years in prison and a fine of up to $ 2 million. The <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> case is being closely followed by Wall Street defense attorneys as a key indication of prosecutors' ability to convince juries of Wall Street crimes, and of the reliability of information supplied by <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who is serving a three-year term on insider trading charges. The purpose of the alleged stock manipulation was to maximize <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>'s profits from the planned sale of a large block of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> stock after a failed takeover of the much larger chemical concern earlier in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> denied the charges in what became the first case to reach the trial phase in a wave of Wall Street corruption investigations by the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office has brought charges in more than 50 securities fraud cases since 1983. Nearly all the claims, however, have involved civil charges. Criminal frauds to date, including pending charges against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, have been settled through plea bargains. The government based its case on the testimony of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> broker <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, an admitted felon expected to play a key role in other securities fraud cases as part of a plea arrangement with the government.
