<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Caterpillar, Steel Industry At Odds Over Quotas</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Feuchter </PERSON> lovingly taps the bright yellow bulldozer awaiting finishing touches on the <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> production line. `` You can hardly point to a part on there that is n't steel,'' he says. Steel is the backbone of <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>'s business, and nobody knows it more intimately than <PERSON> Feuchter </PERSON>, who buys 500,000 tons a year of the metal that winds up in the formidable earth-moving machines under the CAT name. As it searches for the cheapest materials available, <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> finds itself at odds with its major supplier, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry, over quotas that limit imports of foreign steel. Twenty percent of the half-million tons of the steel <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> uses annually comes from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and other countries overseas. The company joined, by a coalition of about 250 mostly small manufacturers, is fighting efforts to extend the quotas. It is a fight not just about trade but about politics. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made a campaign promise to renew the so-called Voluntary Restraint Agreements -LRB- VRAs -RRB- when they expire Sept. 30, and 54 senators are co-sponsoring legislation to extend for five years the VRAs, which limit the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and 19 other countries to a 20 percent share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. Despite complaints from the steel industry, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refused to subject <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to the VRAs in 1984. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, is an ardent champion of free trade and a foe of what he calls the `` fool's gold'' of protectionism. Indeed, in the same letter to Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., pledging to support continuation of the VRAs, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also vowed to press for an international consensus on fair trade that would eliminate the need for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> barrier Even now, top-level <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> trade and economic officials are debating internally just how long the extended VRAs should last and what types of steel they should cover. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> has echoed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s sentiments that the VRAs are a stopgap and the real goal is to end the subsidies, dumping and closed markets that distort the price of steel. It is the first major test of trade policy for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> insists on some protective barrier to shelter its steel industry, how much force will it carry when it insists on dismantling the barriers that protect farmers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>? Political realities at home may force <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> before him, to temper disdain for protectionism against the pressing need to rein in the $ 137 billion trade deficit and bolster a vital <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry that saw 290,000 jobs disappear in the past decade. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry is operating today at 89 percent of capacity, rolling up profits of $ 3 billion in the past two years after being staggered by losses of $ 12 billion in the previous five. Caterpillar and its allies charge the VRAs will force <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to pay artificially high prices for the next five years, impairing their ability to sell goods here and abroad. The VRAs `` cost us dearly,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Trans-Matic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Precision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metalforming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we are ever going to get the trade deficit down, people in manufacturing are going to have to start shipping product out of this country. But before we can do that, we've got to have the material.'' But the steel industry counters vehemently that what is at stake is the survival of the American mills, still struggling to regroup and modernize after the calamitous downturn in the first half of the 1980s. `` The VRAs are in the long-run interests of -LRB- American -RRB- consumers as well as producers,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolff </PERSON>, a former deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative leading the industry fight. `` Obviously in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> everyone wants to buy everything at the lowest possible price now,'' said <PERSON> Wolff </PERSON>. But no other industrialized country `` has considered it acceptable to lose its self-sufficiency in steel.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, president of the USS Division of <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel maker, put it more bluntly at a recent <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> debate on VRAs. `` If we keep putzing around with this VRA question ... more of the industry -LRB- will -RRB- liquidate, and there will be all this handwringing about allocation,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. Caterpillar and its coalition notwithstanding, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> claimed that `` 95 percent of our customers are with us'' in support of the import quotas. `` They've seen a third of the domestic steel industry liquidate -LRB- and -RRB- they know that process can continue. It's in their enlightened self-interest,'' said <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 A few years ago, Peoria-based <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>, like the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry, was on the industrial critical list. The company lost $ 953 million in 1982-84 and saw <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> pose a stiff challenge to its world leadership in the heavy construction field. Big Cat battled back by restructuring factory floors, forging a new relationship with workers, and looking for every possible way to lower costs and stay competitive in the world marketplace. Last year it posted profits of $ 616 million on record sales of $ 10.4 billion, half of them abroad. The weaker dollar helped revive <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>'s fortunes, but company officials say the recovery was also sped by radically altering their production methods to emphasize quality and minimize costs. Stacks of empty parts bins outside one of the Caterpillar plants straddling the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> testify to the company's success in eliminating the need for huge stockpiles of parts Feuchter, manager of central purchasing for <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>'s steel division, said, `` Our chief needs are high quality materials on time and at the right price. VRAs do n't help any of that. They inhibit our ability to shop the best way we know how.'' While steel prices fell during the first two years under VRAs, <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Elder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION>'s manager of governmental affairs, said, `` They were overpriced to begin with.'' He cited a study done for the anti-VRA coalition by the <ORGANIZATION> Stern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a trade advisory group headed by former <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, that concluded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers paid an average of $ 5 billion, or 25 percent, more for steel each year from 1969 through 1985 than their counterparts in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Strong worldwide demand has pushed steel prices up since 1986. Caterpillar blames the quotas for helping push up its prices for plate steel 17 percent a year ago, and for inducing shortages of large tractor track shoes that are only made overseas. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> allowed <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> last summer to import an extra 13,000 tons of the steel track shoes because of the short supply.
