<FIRST>s a BC-Eastern-AssetStripping Adv19   03-18 1184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Asset Stripping, Adv 19,1219</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Papers: Bad Deals Stripped Eastern, Helped Texas Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bargain prices for coveted airport gates and computer reservation systems. Millions in loans from a debt-swamped airline to its growing sister. Money-losing deals to buy fuel from the parent. In court papers, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' recalcitrant pilots make a strong case that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has plotted to suck <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s blood to buoy non-union <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, a key issue as the saga of the strike-decimated carrier moves through bankruptcy proceedings `` Either a sophisticated asset stripping scheme is under way or management is incompetent,'' the pilots state in documents filed in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last week. The pilots cite alleged bargain sales, no-gain loans and money-losing arrangements they say have undermined parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s claim that its affiliated airlines are separate entities. They say <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s management clearly benefited <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s detriment. Eastern, which was losing money long before <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> arrived in 1986, says it transacted above-board, fair-market deals among subsidiaries, with no illicit intermingling of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> blood. Nonetheless, a 59-page court brief filed last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> provides illuminating details that at least raise major questions about Eastern management's behavior. The brief culls information from <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> filings, federal court testimony, a <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report and company financial records to make the case that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> are deeply interwoven. The most striking deal _ `` the red flag on the bull in the bullring'' in the words of one aviation analyst _ was the 1987 transfer of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s coveted computerized reservation system to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> for $ 100 million. At the time, the system was worth at least triple that amount. Moreover, debt-swamped Eastern did n't get a $ 100 million cash infusion from the deal, which it badly needed to support day-to-day operations. Instead it got $ 100 million in notes bearing 6 percent interest _ payable in full in the year 2012. Analysts have questioned the financial wisdom of transferring the computerized reservation system to its new sister. Similar networks soon after fetched $ 280 million, $ 500 million and $ 650 million. Eastern maintains it could n't afford to upgrade its network in a highly competitive battle for travel agents, who book tickets through airline-run computers. Eastern says it was paying $ 130 million a year to operate the network, money it now pays to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> for a better product. The question of whether <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> have been kept separate is central to the bankruptcy proceedings. A judge ultimately could decide whether <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> allowed <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> to languish and refused to merge the two subsidiaries in an attempt to destroy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unions. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> wants to avoid placing its assets on the line to cover <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s more than $ 3 billion in liabilities. `` By keeping the companies separate, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> does n't get the two groups together to be unionized,'' said a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> aviation lawyer who asked not to be identified. `` If he put the two together he would face a situation where if he allowed enough parity of employees that would force an election. `` Then <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has a completely unionized property, which is what he got out of five years ago.'' The pilots' court brief also alleges the following action damaged Eastern: _ Eastern loaned $ 40 million to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> last spring at the same time it was seeking an <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> waiver on a $ 105 million contribution to its pension fund Eastern says the loan was repaid. _ For almost two years <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> failed to demand a non-interest bearing $ 16 million payment due for merger-related expenses from <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> The inaction cost the airline about $ 2.8 million a year in lost interest earnings. Eastern called it a `` bookkeeping transaction'' that has since been paid. _ In March 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> paid <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> $ 25 million for a note worth $ 30 million owned by nearly bankrupt <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> had previously acquired <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> made $ 4.4 million on the deal. The pilots called it a senseless investment since <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> had no creditworthiness and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> needed to conserve cash. _ Eastern paid $ 22 million to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> for strike-related services in December 1987 and another $ 19 million last fall for similar services that have not been used Eastern maintains the money was well-spent. _ <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, the pilots claim, disproportionate gained from a merger of sales offices with Eastern in January 1987 Eastern brought in 166 offices while <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> contributed 27. The arrangement was dissolved last December. _ <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> paid $ 11 million to Eastern for 11 <ORGANIZATION> Newark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> gates allegedly worth twice as much The court papers compare the deal with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s 1986 sale of eight <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, gates to <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> for $ 25 million. Eastern says it got the market price. _ A fuel purchase agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> costs Eastern about $ 18 million annually but provides no apparent savings, the papers state Eastern claims it saves $ 6 million a year. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> claims the arrangement merges purchases of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, giving them greater clout with suppliers. _ The pending sale of the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> shuttle to <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for $ 365 million will reduce <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s cash flow by $ 30 million to $ 40 million, the pilots say The airline says sale of the shuttle, despite its profitability, is necessary for the airline's survival. The pilots claim downsizing Eastern last year by closing its <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, hub and selling planes, routes and airport gates as part of $ 130 million in asset sales has hurt profitability while benefiting <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. They also say most of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s directors and managers used to work at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> or both _ and do n't have <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s best interests in mind. Another key issue involves <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pension obligations _ put at $ 320 million by the company but $ 750 million by the federal <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guarantee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>. Under federal law, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> could be held liable for the total underfunding of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pension plans. If Eastern fails to make a $ 100 million payment due in September, lawyers said, the government could tap money from elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Air structure. To guarantee payment, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> may sell more assets. The pilots' court papers ask Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> to appoint a trustee to run Eastern during bankruptcy proceedings, charging that <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> would continue dismantling <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and try to break its unions, as he did after taking <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy in 1983. `` It may not win over the long run but it certainly puts a lot of flies in the ointment in terms of trying to get the assets sold piecemeal,'' said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Marckesano </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Janney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. But lawyers said obtaining a trustee is difficult and may be viewed by <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> as unnecessary. Moreover, the judge may not view Eastern management's sale of assets and other actions as irresponsible. `` These asset sales have kept Eastern in business,'' Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. `` Without these sales, this company would have gone belly-up a long time ago.'' End adv for Sunday, March 19
