<HEAD>For release weekend editions Adv 18-19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health Perils of the Pits: Pencil Stabs, Hypertension, `Your Normal
Stuff'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs for UNDATED item on Business Enterprise Digest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As veteran Fire Department paramedics working some of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s meanest streets, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Guzzardo </PERSON> thought they'd seen just about everything. Then they they took part-time jobs staffing the medical office at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. `` The one I'll never forget,'' said <PERSON> Guzzardo </PERSON>, `` is the time a guy came in here with part of a pencil sticking out of his chest. I mean, it gets rough in the -LRB- trading -RRB- pits every so often, and we get lots of guys stabbed with pencils. `` Hands are pretty common and every once in a while, a guy will get stuck in the face. But this guy got it in the chest and the poor guy was panicking so much, we pulled it out ourselves instead of sending him over to the hospital. `` And as soon as we finished bandaging him up,'' <PERSON> Guzzardo </PERSON> said, `` he puts his jacket back on and went back to trade.'' <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> nods, then adds, `` Thank God they're making pencils out of graphite. `` Because if they were still using lead, we'd have lost a few guys.'' To be truthful, a typical day at the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s medical office, located just a few stops down the marble-paneled hallway from the coat room of the sprawling futures market, is less like an episode of the television series `` M.A.S.H'' than a commercial for <ORGANIZATION> Maytag </ORGANIZATION> appliances. An average of 10 to 15 traders find their way into the office each day, about half for what amounts to regularly scheduled maintenance and the other half for `` cuts and bruises, flu, your normal stuff,'' said <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>. `` We monitor about 200 guys on a regular basis ... blood pressure, headaches and dizziness, the occasional diabetic. The funny thing,'' he said, `` is that people probably guess with all the pressure and high stakes around this place, we'd get lots of guys coming in ... hyperventilating and such. `` But I've been here since they opened the office and never once has a guy come in here, sweating or bug-eyed or anything and said, ` Jeez, I just lost my shirt.' `` Most of the guys with a history of high blood pressure or heart troubles are under the regular care of the doctor. We see them at the beginning of the day or the end,'' he said. `` You can never get a feel for what's going on in the pits by what happens in here.'' The medical office was created in 1978 in case of health emergencies at the fast-growing exchange, a leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> center for trading futures contracts in items that range from grains to soybeans to <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds. Today if offers a range of services and equipment far beyond its humble origins. In the beginning, <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> notes, pointing to a small photo on the wall, the `` office'' was a cabinet with a single oxygen tank inside. Today, it boasts emergency life-support and state-of-the-art heart and respiratory monitoring systems and is staffed by six <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> paramedics working on a revolving basis during their 36 hours between shifts. Despite having worked at the Board of Trade for 10 years, <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> said he does little other than keeping abreast of how some of the commodities traded there might be doing _ strictly for the sake of conversation _ and `` does n't dabble.'' `` No way,'' he said. `` You might hear somebody say something about this or that or the other, but it's something I'd never get into. `` Look,'' he added, `` I've got more than enough stress in my regular job.''
</TEXT>
