<HEAD>CHICAGO: regular job.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Here are some commodity price trends for the past week: Soybean and corn futures prices advanced, but wheat slipped on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat for delivery in March settled Friday at $ 4.34 a bushel. down from $ 4.36 a week earlier; March corn climbed to $ 2.78 \ a bushel from $ 2.75 -LCB-; March oats rose to $ 2.08 a bushel from $ 2.07; and soybeans rose to $ 7.69 a bushel from $ 7.57 Livestock and pork futures mostly were lower at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. April live cattle was unchanged at 78.05 cents a pound; March feeder cattle slipped to 79.67 cents a pound from 81.25 cents; April live hogs were 42.72 cents a pound; down from 43.65 cents; and March frozen pork bellies slipped to 36.95 cents a pound from 38.45 cents. Gold futures declined but silver futures were higher on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. April gold slipped to $ 393.60 a troy ounce from $ 389.30; May silver rose to $ 6.195 a troy ounce from $ 6.150. Energy futures made impressive gains on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. West Texas Intermediate crude oil for April delivery zoomed to $ 20.33 a barrel from $ 18.50; April heating oil climbed to 53.57 cents a gallon from 51.19 cents; and April unleaded gasoline rose to 55.62 cents a gallon from 51.78 cents.
